===Etymology===
From Middle English {{term|bemoth|lang=enm}}, {{term|behemoth|lang=enm}}, from Late Latin, from {{etyl|he}} {{term|בהמות|tr=bəhēmōth|sc=Hebr}}, either an intensive plural of {{term|בהמה|tr=bəhēmāh|sc=Hebr}} 'beast', from {{proto|Semitic}} (compare Ethiopic {{term||bəhma}} 'dumb, speechless', Arabic {{term||ʼabham}} (declined as ''bahma(t)'', ''bahīma(t)'') 'animal'), or borrowed from Ancient Egyptian {{term|p-ehe-mau|lang=egy}} 'hippopotamus', literally 'water-ox'.

